HIAL Project Theory and Assignment Deep Dive

This document explains the full logic of the HIAL assignment in a continuous theory-first format. The project combines preference-based reward learning and reinforcement learning from demonstrations (RLfD) for a UR5 food-serving task: pick a banana and place it on a plate. The key challenge is that the native environment reward is sparse, so direct trial-and-error learning is inefficient. The assignment addresses this by first recovering a dense reward proxy from human preferences and then using that learned reward to train control policies.

\section*{Problem Setting and Motivation}

The environment state is goal-conditioned and represented by a dictionary with observation, achieved goal, and desired goal. The observation includes robot kinematics and object dynamics; the desired goal is the fixed plate center. The action is continuous and controls end-effector displacement plus gripper opening/closing.

The task reward provided by the simulator is sparse: success yields a large positive terminal value, while non-success steps receive a small negative penalty. Sparse rewards are problematic because early random policies almost never hit success states, producing weak learning signals and high sample complexity. The assignment therefore asks for preference-based reward recovery before policy learning.

\section*{Data: What We Actually Have}

The project has several data sources that play different roles.

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Expert demonstrations in \texttt{demo\_data/PickAndPlace} contain episodic trajectories with arrays for states, actions, next states, rewards, and done flags.
  \item Video clips generated from expert and random rollouts act as visual query objects for human preference collection.
  \item Trajectory-level feature vectors summarize each clip through hand-designed geometric signals.
  \item Human preference responses over clip pairs provide supervised information about relative trajectory quality.
  \item Replay buffer data stores transition tuples used by off-policy RL updates.
\end{itemize}

An expert demo episode can be written as
\[
\tau = \{(s_0,a_0,s_1,d_0), \ldots, (s_{T-1},a_{T-1},s_T,d_{T-1})\}.
\]
These episodes are not only replay assets; they are used to initialize policy learning so the agent starts from behaviorally relevant regions of state-action space.

\section*{Phase 1.1: Trajectory Features and Clip Dataset}

The first assignment block asks for two outputs: trajectory features and 30 clips (20 expert + 10 random). In implementation terms, \texttt{alg/banana.py} does the following:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Builds the wrapped environment (\texttt{ResetWrapper}, \texttt{ActionNormalizer}, \texttt{TimeLimitWrapper}).
  \item Replays each expert action sequence and records frames.
  \item Rolls out random policies for additional contrastive trajectories.
  \item Computes a feature vector per trajectory and stores all metadata in \texttt{saved/trajectory\_records.json}.
\end{enumerate}

The feature map is trajectory-level:
\[
\phi(\tau) = [f_1(\tau), f_2(\tau), f_3(\tau)].
\]
In this project, features are distance-based (arm-to-banana and banana-to-plate statistics). Distances are negated so higher values correspond to better trajectories:
\[
f_1 = -\min_t d(\text{ee}_t,\text{banana}_t), \quad
f_2 = -\min_t d(\text{banana}_t,\text{goal}), \quad
f_3 = -d(\text{banana}_T,\text{goal}).
\]
This gives a compact trajectory quality representation that is differentiable with respect to behavior quality but independent of sparse environment reward.

\section*{Phase 1.2: Preference Learning with APReL}

The second block asks to recover reward weights from human pairwise preferences using APReL. The central assumption is a linear reward model:
\[
R_w(\tau) = w^\top \phi(\tau),
\]
where $w$ is unknown and must be inferred from comparison feedback.

The implemented \texttt{alg/pref\_learn.py} pipeline:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Loads trajectory records and converts them into an APReL \texttt{TrajectorySet}.
  \item Initializes a user model and belief over reward weights.
  \item Uses \texttt{QueryOptimizerDiscreteTrajectorySet} with a pairwise \texttt{PreferenceQuery} template.
  \item Repeats for 10 queries: optimize query, ask human, update posterior belief.
  \item Saves posterior-mean weights to \texttt{saved/feature\_weights.csv}.
\end{enumerate}

At a conceptual level, each response imposes relative constraints such as
\[
\tau_A \succ \tau_B \;\Longrightarrow\; w^\top\phi(\tau_A) > w^\top\phi(\tau_B),
\]
and Bayesian updates gradually concentrate belief mass around weights consistent with observed choices.

Active query selection via an acquisition function (e.g., mutual information) improves label efficiency by selecting the most informative trajectory pairs under current uncertainty.

\section*{Phase 2: RL from Demonstrations with Learned Reward}

The policy-learning phase asks for an episodic training loop with post-hoc reward recovery. This is implemented in \texttt{alg/policy\_learn.py} (SAC version), and conceptually follows:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Pre-fill replay buffer with expert transitions.
  \item Roll out current policy for one full episode.
  \item Compute trajectory features and reward with current learned weights.
  \item Distribute trajectory reward across episode steps and add transitions to replay buffer.
  \item Update policy using off-policy gradient steps.
  \item Evaluate every 1k environment steps over 10 randomized test runs.
\end{enumerate}

Trajectory reward is computed as
\[
R(\tau) = w^\top\phi(\tau),
\]
and transformed into per-transition labels as
\[
r_t = \frac{R(\tau)}{T}.
\]
This is a practical post-hoc reward assignment that preserves the assignment's episodic requirement while remaining compatible with standard off-policy replay mechanisms.

\section*{Why Demonstrations Help Learning}

Without demonstration seeding, early replay data is dominated by low-quality random behavior. Expert prefill changes the initial data distribution:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Critic targets become informative earlier.
  \item Actor updates are anchored around successful manipulation patterns.
  \item Exploration burden is reduced in sparse-reward regions.
\end{itemize}

This is exactly the motivation of RLfD: demonstrations improve sample efficiency while RL still enables further policy improvement.

\section*{SAC and AWAC in This Context}

SAC is a strong continuous-control baseline with entropy-regularized actor updates and twin-critic value estimation. AWAC emphasizes advantage-weighted behavior fitting, often particularly effective in offline/online demonstration-rich settings. In this project, SAC satisfies the required assignment; AWAC provides an additional comparison and can be used for deeper analysis.

\section*{Extra Credit Theory: Single-Loop Online Integration}

The optional extra credit removes strict phase separation and asks for an online loop where reward learning and policy learning interact each episode:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Ask for new human preferences.
  \item Update reward belief and recover new weights.
  \item Roll out current policy and compute rewards with those updated weights.
  \item Update the policy.
  \item Add new rollout trajectory and clip to the preference set for future querying.
\end{enumerate}

This creates a closed feedback loop between reward inference and control learning. Mathematically, both the reward estimate $w_k$ and policy $\pi_k$ evolve over episodes:
\[
w_{k+1} \leftarrow \text{BeliefUpdate}(w_k,\text{new preferences}), \qquad
\pi_{k+1} \leftarrow \text{RLUpdate}(\pi_k, R_{w_{k+1}}).
\]
The approach is more adaptive but operationally heavier because it requires ongoing human interaction.

\section*{Code-to-Assignment Mapping}

The project requirements map directly to the following scripts:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \texttt{alg/banana.py}: feature design + 30 clips + trajectory records.
  \item \texttt{alg/pref\_learn.py}: APReL preference loop + learned weight export.
  \item \texttt{alg/policy\_learn.py}: episodic RLfD with learned reward and checkpointed training.
  \item \texttt{alg/policy\_test.py}: TA-facing policy loading and action query API.
\end{itemize}

Expected artifacts in \texttt{saved/} include clips, trajectory records, learned feature weights, policy checkpoints, and learning curves.

\section*{Conclusion}

The assignment is a full pipeline from subjective human preference to executable robot behavior:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item features encode trajectory semantics,
  \item APReL converts pairwise preferences into a reward model,
  \item RLfD uses that model plus demonstrations to learn a control policy.
\end{itemize}

Conceptually, preference learning answers what should be optimized, while policy learning answers how to optimize it in continuous control.

